NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There are several main reasons to duck an Ace. One is to disrupt communications. On this hand, for example, if Moe ducks the Ace until the 3rd round, then Azin must use an entry to cash the fourth heart. That is the most common reason to duck the Ace. Another reason that comes up occasionally is suppose dummy has a long solid suit missing the Ace with no side entries. In that case the partner of the person holding the Ace should give count, and the defender should hold up on the Ace until he is sure declarer has played the last card of the suit. Again, you are disrupting communications.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The most common other reason is let's say dummy (North) has KQ10 of a suit and let us say East (behind North) has the Ace but not the Jack. Suppose declarer leads that suit and plays the King. East should duck smoothly. Now, in order to get two tricks declarer may get back to his hand and lead the suit again assuming West has the Ace. But if declarer plays the Queen then East wins the Ace and their sides Jack is good. If East had taken the first trick, then declarer would have no choice but to finesse the 10 to get 2 tricks. |
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, ducking the Ace to hide where it is, is another reason to duck. Having said that, it is rare that ducking is right. So, in general, so long as the Ace captures an honor, it is okay to take it.|
